<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>Much as I'd like to believe this, I was recently having a discussion with a neuroscience researcher where he talked about this natural phenomenon they've observed. Infants are on this side of the line craving novelty and mastery while aged folks are on the opposite end with comfort and familiarity. Everyone else lies sequentially in between.<p>That made a lot of sense to me. No doubt we can override it but...this kind of predisposition does place restrictions that one may not otherwise account for.<p>Plus, what better time than NOW!<p><i>I say this as I study for midterms</i></font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=240></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_3145165 href="vote?for=3145165&dir=up&whence=%2f%78%3f%66%6e%69%64%3d%58%6f%39%46%70%4c%33%74%75%75"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_3145165></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=carbocation">carbocation</a> 104 days ago  | <a href="item?id=3145165">link</a></span></div><br>
